# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cloud-cost-optimization
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/autoscaling] Autoscaling differs from having a fixed daily, weekly, or yearly cycle of server use in that it is responsive to actual usage patterns, and thus reduces the potential downside of having too few or too many servers for the traffic load.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/autoscaling] For instance, if traffic is usually lower at midnight, then a static scaling solution might schedule some servers to sleep at night, but this might result in downtime on a night where people happen to use the Internet more (for instance, due to a viral news event).
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/autoscaling] Autoscaling, on the other hand, can handle unexpected traffic spikes better.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/autoscaling] In the list below, we use the terminology used by Amazon Web Services (AWS).
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/autoscaling] However, alternative names are noted and terminology that is specific to the names of Amazon services is not used for the names.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/autoscaling] Amazon Web Services launched the Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2) service in August 2006, that allowed developers to programmatically create and terminate instances (machines).
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/autoscaling] At the time of initial launch, AWS did not offer autoscaling, but the ability to programmatically create and terminate instances gave developers the flexibility to write their own code for autoscaling.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/autoscaling] Third-party autoscaling software for AWS began appearing around April 2008.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/autoscaling] These included tools by Scalr and RightScale.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/autoscaling] RightScale was used by Animoto, which was able to handle Facebook traffic by adopting autoscaling.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/autoscaling] On May 18, 2009, Amazon launched its own autoscaling feature along with Elastic Load Balancing, as part of Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/autoscaling] Autoscaling is now an integral component of Amazon's EC2 offering.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/autoscaling] Autoscaling on Amazon Web Services is done through a web browser or the command line tool.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/autoscaling] In May 2016 Autoscaling was also offered in AWS ECS Service.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/autoscaling] On-demand video provider Netflix documented their use of autoscaling with Amazon Web Services to meet their highly variable consumer needs.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/autoscaling] They found that aggressive scaling up and delayed and cautious scaling down served their goals of uptime and responsiveness best.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/autoscaling] In an article for *TechCrunch*, Zev Laderman, the co-founder and CEO of Newvem, a service that helps optimize AWS cloud infrastructure, recommended that startups use autoscaling in order to keep their Amazon Web Services costs low.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/autoscaling] Various best practice guides for AWS use suggest using its autoscaling feature even in cases where the load is not variable.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/autoscaling] Netflix's internal best practices require every instance to be in an autoscaling group, and its conformity monkey terminates any instance not in an autoscaling group in order to enforce this best practice.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/autoscaling] On June 27, 2013, Microsoft announced that it was adding autoscaling support to its Windows Azure cloud computing platform.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/autoscaling] Documentation for the feature is available on the Microsoft Developer Network.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/autoscaling] Oracle Cloud Platform allows server instances to automatically scale a cluster in or out by defining an auto-scaling rule.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/autoscaling] These rules are based on CPU and/or memory utilization and determine when to add or remove nodes.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/autoscaling] On November 17, 2014, the Google Compute Engine announced a public beta of its autoscaling feature for use in Google Cloud Platform applications.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/autoscaling] As of March 2015, the autoscaling tool is still in Beta.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/autoscaling] In a blog post in August 2014, a Facebook engineer disclosed that the company had started using autoscaling to bring down its energy costs.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/autoscaling] The blog post reported a 27% decline in energy use for low traffic hours (around midnight) and a 10-15% decline in energy use over the typical 24-hour cycle.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/autoscaling] Autoscaling by default uses *reactive* decision approach for dealing with traffic scaling: scaling only happens in response to real-time changes in metrics.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/autoscaling] In some cases, particularly when the changes occur very quickly, this reactive approach to scaling is insufficient.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/autoscaling] Two other kinds of autoscaling decision approaches are described below.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/autoscaling] This is an approach to autoscaling where changes are made to the minimum size, maximum size, or desired capacity of the autoscaling group at specific times of day.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/autoscaling] Scheduled scaling is useful, for instance, if there is a known traffic load increase or decrease at specific times of the day, but the change is too sudden for reactive approach based autoscaling to respond fast enough.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/autoscaling] AWS autoscaling groups support scheduled scaling.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/autoscaling] This approach to autoscaling uses predictive analytics.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/autoscaling] The idea is to combine recent usage trends with historical usage data as well as other kinds of data to predict usage in the future, and autoscale based on these predictions.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/autoscaling] For parts of their infrastructure and specific workloads, Netflix found that Scryer, their predictive analytics engine, gave better results than Amazon's reactive autoscaling approach.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/autoscaling] On November 20, 2018, AWS announced that predictive scaling would be available as part of its autoscaling offering.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/capacity-planning] The phrase is also used in business computing and information technology as a synonym for capacity management.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/capacity-planning] IT capacity planning involves estimating the storage, computer hardware, software and connection infrastructure resources required over some future period of time.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/capacity-planning] A common concern of enterprises is whether the required resources are in place to handle an increase in users or number of interactions.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/capacity-planning] Capacity management is concerned about adding central processing units (CPUs), memory and storage to a physical or virtual server.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/capacity-planning] This has been the traditional and vertical way of scaling up web applications, however IT capacity planning has been developed with the goal of forecasting the requirements for this vertical scaling approach.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/capacity-planning] A discrepancy between the capacity of an organization and the demands of its customers results in inefficiency, either in under-utilized resources or unfulfilled customer demand.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/capacity-planning] The goal of capacity planning is to minimize this discrepancy.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/capacity-planning] Demand for an organization's capacity varies based on changes in production output, such as increasing or decreasing the production quantity of an existing product, or producing new products.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/capacity-planning] Better utilization of existing capacity can be accomplished through improvements in overall equipment effectiveness (OEE).
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/capacity-planning] Capacity can be increased through introducing new techniques, equipment and materials, increasing the number of workers or machines, increasing the number of shifts, or acquiring additional production facilities.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/capacity-planning] Capacity is calculated as (number of machines or workers) × (number of shifts) × (utilization) × (efficiency).
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/capacity-planning] They must all account both for current capacity as well as possible future scaling.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/capacity-planning] The broad classes of capacity planning are lead strategy, lag strategy, match strategy, and adjustment strategy.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/capacity-planning] Advantage of lead strategy: First, it ensures that the organization has adequate capacity to meet all demand, even during periods of high growth.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/capacity-planning] This is especially important when the availability of a product or service is crucial, as in the case of emergency care or hot new product.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/capacity-planning] For many new products, being late to market can mean the difference between success and failure.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/capacity-planning] Another advantage of a lead capacity strategy is that it can be used to preempt competitors who might be planning to expand their own capacity.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/capacity-planning] Being the first in an area to open a large grocery or home improvement store gives a retailer a define edge.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/capacity-planning] Finally many businesses find that overbuilding in anticipation of increased usage is cheaper and less disruptive than constantly making small increases in capacity.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/capacity-planning] Of course, a lead capacity strategy can be very risky, particularly if demand is unpredictable or technology is evolving rapidly.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/capacity-planning] One simple model distinguishes between short-, mid-, and long-term capacity planning (operational, tactical, and strategical, respectively).
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/capacity-planning] These range from a few days to many years in the future.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/capacity-planning] In the context of systems engineering, capacity planning is used during system design and system performance monitoring....
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/capacity-planning] Capacity planning is long-term decision that establishes a firm's overall level resources.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/capacity-planning] It extends over a time horizon long enough to obtain resources.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/capacity-planning] Capacity decisions affect the production lead time, customer responsiveness, operating cost and company ability to compete.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/capacity-planning] Inadequate capacity planning can lead to the loss of the customer and business.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/capacity-planning] Excess capacity can drain the company's resources and prevent investments into more lucrative ventures.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/capacity-planning] The question of when capacity should be increased and by how much are the critical decisions.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/capacity-planning] Failure to make these decisions correctly can be especially damaging to the overall performance when time delays are present in the system.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/capacity-planning] From a scheduling perspective it is very easy to determine how much capacity (or time) will be required to manufacture a quantity of parts.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/capacity-planning] Simply multiply the standard cycle time by the number of parts and divide by the part or process OEE %.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/capacity-planning] (500 parts × 30 seconds) / 85% = 17647.1 seconds The OEE index makes it easy to determine whether we have ample capacity to run the required production.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/capacity-planning] In this example 4.2 hours at standard versus 4.9 hours based on the OEE index.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/capacity-planning] By repeating this process for all the parts that run through a given machine, it is possible to determine the total capacity required to run production.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/capacity-planning] When considering new work for a piece of equipment or machinery, knowing how much capacity is available to run the work will eventually become part of the overall process.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/capacity-planning] Typically, an annual forecast is used to determine how many hours per year are required.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/capacity-planning] To calculate the total capacity available, the volume is adjusted according to the period being considered.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/capacity-planning] The available capacity is the difference between the required capacity and planned operating capacity.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/capacity-planning] Capacity is needed in formulation and execution of strategy as this refers to how capable are the resources in the organization.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/capacity-planning] Without effective resources it could be very difficult to formulate and implement the Strategy.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] In 2011, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) identified five "essential characteristics" for cloud systems.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] By 2023, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) had expanded and refined the list.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] The history of cloud computing extends to the 1960s, with the initial concepts of time-sharing becoming popularized via remote job entry (RJE).
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] The "data center" model, where users submitted jobs to operators to run on mainframes, was predominantly used during this era.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] This period saw broad experimentation with making large-scale computing power more accessible through time-sharing, while optimizing infrastructure, platforms, and applications to improve efficiency for end users.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] The "cloud" metaphor for virtualized services dates to 1994, when it was used by General Magic for the universe of "places" that mobile agents in the Telescript environment could "go".
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] The metaphor is credited to David Hoffman, a General Magic communications specialist, based on its long-standing use in networking and telecom.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] The expression *cloud computing* became more widely known in 1996 when Compaq Computer Corporation drew up a business plan for future computing and the Internet.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] The company's ambition was to supercharge sales with "cloud computing-enabled applications".
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] The business plan foresaw that online consumer file storage would likely be commercially successful.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] As a result, Compaq decided to sell server hardware to internet service providers.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] In the 2000s, the application of cloud computing began to take shape with the establishment of Amazon Web Services (AWS) in 2002, which allowed developers to build applications independently.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] In 2006 Amazon Simple Storage Service, known as Amazon S3, and the Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2) were released.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] In 2008 NASA's development of the first open-source software for deploying private and hybrid clouds.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] The following decade saw the launch of various cloud services.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] In 2010, Microsoft launched Microsoft Azure, and Rackspace Hosting and NASA initiated an open-source cloud-software project, OpenStack.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] IBM introduced the IBM SmartCloud framework in 2011, and Oracle announced the Oracle Cloud in 2012.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] In December 2019, Amazon launched AWS Outposts, a service that extends AWS infrastructure, services, APIs, and tools to customer data centers, co-location spaces, or on-premises facilities.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Cloud computing can shorten time to market by offering pre-configured tools, scalable resources, and managed services, allowing users to focus on core business value rather than maintaining infrastructure.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Cloud platforms can enable organizations and individuals to reduce upfront capital expenditures on physical infrastructure by shifting to an operational expenditure model, where costs scale with usage.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Cloud platforms also offer managed services and tools, such as artificial intelligence, data analytics, and machine learning, which might otherwise require significant in-house expertise and infrastructure investment.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] While cloud computing can offer cost advantages through effective resource optimization, organizations often face challenges such as unused resources, inefficient configurations, and hidden costs without proper oversight and governance.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Many cloud platforms provide cost management tools, such as AWS Cost Explorer and Azure Cost Management, and frameworks like FinOps have emerged to standardize financial operations in the cloud.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Cloud computing also facilitates collaboration, remote work, and global service delivery by enabling secure access to data and applications from any location with an internet connection.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Cloud providers offer various redundancy options for core services, such as managed storage and managed databases, though redundancy configurations often vary by service tier.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Advanced redundancy strategies, such as cross-region replication or failover systems, typically require explicit configuration and may incur additional costs or licensing fees.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Cloud environments operate under a shared responsibility model, where providers are typically responsible for infrastructure security, physical hardware, and software updates, while customers are accountable for data encryption, identity and access management (IAM), and application-level security.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] The decision to adopt cloud computing or maintain on-premises infrastructure depends on factors such as scalability, cost structure, latency requirements, regulatory constraints, and infrastructure customization.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Organizations with variable or unpredictable workloads, limited capital for upfront investments, or a focus on rapid scalability benefit from cloud adoption.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Startups, SaaS companies, and e-commerce platforms often prefer the pay-as-you-go operational expenditure (OpEx) model of cloud infrastructure.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Additionally, companies prioritizing global accessibility, remote workforce enablement, disaster recovery, and leveraging advanced services such as AI/ML and analytics are well-suited for the cloud.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] In recent years, some cloud providers have started offering specialized services for high-performance computing and low-latency applications, addressing some use cases previously exclusive to on-premises setups.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] On the other hand, organizations with strict regulatory requirements, highly predictable workloads, or reliance on deeply integrated legacy systems may find cloud infrastructure less suitable.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Businesses in industries like defense, government, or those handling highly sensitive data often favor on-premises setups for greater control and data sovereignty.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Additionally, companies with ultra-low latency requirements, such as high-frequency trading (HFT) firms, rely on custom hardware (e.g., FPGAs) and physical proximity to exchanges, which most cloud providers cannot fully replicate despite recent advancements.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Similarly, tech giants like Google, Meta, and Amazon build their own data centers due to economies of scale, predictable workloads, and the ability to customize hardware and network infrastructure for optimal efficiency.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] However, these companies also use cloud services selectively for certain workloads and applications where it aligns with their operational needs.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] In practice, many organizations are increasingly adopting hybrid cloud architectures, combining on-premises infrastructure with cloud services.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] This approach allows businesses to balance scalability, cost-effectiveness, and control, offering the benefits of both deployment models while mitigating their respective limitations.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] One of the primary challenges of cloud computing, compared with traditional on-premises systems, is maintaining data security and privacy.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Cloud users entrust their sensitive data to third-party providers, who may not have adequate measures to protect it from unauthorized access, breaches, or leaks.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Cloud users also face compliance risks if they have to adhere to certain regulations or standards regarding data protection, such as GDPR or HIPAA.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Another challenge of cloud computing is reduced visibility and control.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Cloud users may not have full insight into how their cloud resources are managed, configured, or optimized by their providers.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] They may also have limited ability to customize or modify their cloud services according to their specific needs or preferences.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Complete understanding of all technology may be impossible, especially given the scale, complexity, and deliberate opacity of contemporary systems; however, there is a need for understanding complex technologies and their interconnections to have power and agency within them.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] The metaphor of the cloud can be seen as problematic as cloud computing retains the aura of something noumenal and numinous; it is something experienced without precisely understanding what it is or how it works.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Additionally, cloud migration is a significant challenge.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] This process involves transferring data, applications, or workloads from one cloud environment to another, or from on-premises infrastructure to the cloud.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Cloud migration can be complicated, time-consuming, and expensive, particularly when there are compatibility issues between different cloud platforms or architectures.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] If not carefully planned and executed, cloud migration can lead to downtime, reduced performance, or even data loss.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Applications hosted in the cloud are susceptible to the fallacies of distributed computing, a series of misconceptions that can lead to significant issues in software development and deployment.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] In a report by Gartner, a survey of 200 IT leaders revealed that 69% experienced budget overruns in their organizations' cloud expenditures during 2023.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Conversely, 31% of IT leaders whose organizations stayed within budget attributed their success to accurate forecasting and budgeting, proactive monitoring of spending, and effective optimization.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] The 2024 Flexera State of Cloud Report identifies the top cloud challenges as managing cloud spend, followed by security concerns and lack of expertise.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Public cloud expenditures exceeded budgeted amounts by an average of 15%.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] The report also reveals that cost savings is the top cloud initiative for 60% of respondents.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Furthermore, 65% measure cloud progress through cost savings, while 42% prioritize shorter time-to-market, indicating that cloud's promise of accelerated deployment is often overshadowed by cost concerns.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Typically, cloud providers' Service Level Agreements (SLAs) do not encompass all forms of service interruptions.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Exclusions typically include planned maintenance, downtime resulting from external factors such as network issues, human errors, like misconfigurations, natural disasters, force majeure events, or security breaches.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Typically, customers bear the responsibility of monitoring SLA compliance and must file claims for any unmet SLAs within a designated timeframe.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Customers should be aware of how deviations from SLAs are calculated, as these parameters may vary by service.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] These requirements can place a considerable burden on customers.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Additionally, SLA percentages and conditions can differ across various services within the same provider, with some services lacking any SLA altogether.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] In cases of service interruptions due to hardware failures in the cloud provider, the company typically does not offer monetary compensation.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Instead, eligible users may receive credits as outlined in the corresponding SLA.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Cloud computing abstractions aim to simplify resource management, but leaky abstractions can expose underlying complexities.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] These variations in abstraction quality depend on the cloud vendor, service and architecture.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Mitigating leaky abstractions requires users to understand the implementation details and limitations of the cloud services they utilize.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Service lock-in within the same vendor occurs when a customer becomes dependent on specific services within a cloud vendor, making it challenging to switch to alternative services within the same vendor when their needs change.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Cloud computing poses privacy concerns because the service provider can access the data that is in the cloud at any time.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] It could accidentally or deliberately alter or delete information.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Many cloud providers can share information with third parties if necessary for purposes of law and order without a warrant.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] That is permitted in their privacy policies, which users must agree to before they start using cloud services.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Solutions to privacy include policy and legislation as well as end-users' choices for how data is stored.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Users can encrypt data that is processed or stored within the cloud to prevent unauthorized access.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Identity management systems can also provide practical solutions to privacy concerns in cloud computing.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] These systems distinguish between authorized and unauthorized users and determine the amount of data that is accessible to each entity.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] The systems work by creating and describing identities, recording activities, and getting rid of unused identities.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] According to the Cloud Security Alliance, the top three threats in the cloud are *Insecure Interfaces and APIs*, *Data Loss & Leakage*, and *Hardware Failure*—which accounted for 29%, 25% and 10% of all cloud security outages respectively.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Together, these form shared technology vulnerabilities.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] In a cloud provider platform being shared by different users, there may be a possibility that information belonging to different customers resides on the same data server.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Additionally, Eugene Schultz, chief technology officer at Emagined Security, said that hackers are spending substantial time and effort looking for ways to penetrate the cloud.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] "There are some real Achilles' heels in the cloud infrastructure that are making big holes for the bad guys to get into".
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Because data from hundreds or thousands of companies can be stored on large cloud servers, hackers can theoretically gain control of huge stores of information through a single attack—a process he called "hyperjacking".
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Some examples of this include the Dropbox security breach, and iCloud 2014 leak.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Dropbox had been breached in October 2014, having over seven million of its users passwords stolen by hackers in an effort to get monetary value from it by Bitcoins (BTC).
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] By having these passwords, they are able to read private data as well as have this data be indexed by search engines (making the information public).
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] There is the problem of legal ownership of the data (If a user stores some data in the cloud, can the cloud provider profit from it?).
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Many Terms of Service agreements are silent on the question of ownership.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Physical control of the computer equipment (private cloud) is more secure than having the equipment off-site and under someone else's control (public cloud).
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] This delivers great incentive to public cloud computing service providers to prioritize building and maintaining strong management of secure services.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Some small businesses that do not have expertise in IT security could find that it is more secure for them to use a public cloud.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] There is the risk that end users do not understand the issues involved when signing on to a cloud service (persons sometimes do not read the many pages of the terms of service agreement, and just click "Accept" without reading).
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] This is important now that cloud computing is common and required for some services to work, for example for an intelligent personal assistant (Apple's Siri or Google Assistant).
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Fundamentally, private cloud is seen as more secure with higher levels of control for the owner, however public cloud is seen to be more flexible and requires less time and money investment from the user.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] The attacks that can be made on cloud computing systems include man-in-the middle attacks, phishing attacks, authentication attacks, and malware attacks.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] One of the largest threats is considered to be malware attacks, such as Trojan horses.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Recent research conducted in 2022 has revealed that the Trojan horse injection method is a serious problem with harmful impacts on cloud computing systems.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] The CLOUD Act allows United States authorities to request data from cloud providers, and courts can impose nondisclosure requirements preventing providers from notifying affected users.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] This framework is in legal tension with Article 48 of the European General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which restricts the transfer of personal data in response to foreign court or administrative orders unless based on an international agreement.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] As a result, cloud service providers operating in both Europe and the U.S. may face competing legal obligations.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Donohue writing for the *Harvard Journal of Law and Public Policy*, cloud service providers also fall within the broader category of service providers subject to Section 702 of the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act (FISA), which has had documented effects on cloud providers and their customers.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] The National Institute of Standards and Technology recognized three cloud service models in 2011: Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), and Software as a Service (SaaS).
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] The International Organization for Standardization (ISO) later identified additional models in 2023, including "Network as a Service", "Communications as a Service", "Compute as a Service", and "Data Storage as a Service".
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Infrastructure as a service (IaaS) refers to online services that provide high-level APIs used to abstract various low-level details of underlying network infrastructure like physical computing resources, location, data partitioning, scaling, security, backup, etc.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] A hypervisor runs the virtual machines as guests.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Pools of hypervisors within the cloud operational system can support large numbers of virtual machines and the ability to scale services up and down according to customers' varying requirements.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Linux containers run in isolated partitions of a single Linux kernel running directly on the physical hardware.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Linux cgroups and namespaces are the underlying Linux kernel technologies used to isolate, secure and manage the containers.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] The use of containers offers higher performance than virtualization because there is no hypervisor overhead.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] IaaS clouds often offer additional resources such as a virtual-machine disk-image library, raw block storage, file or object storage, firewalls, load balancers, IP addresses, virtual local area networks (VLANs), and software bundles.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] The NIST's definition of cloud computing describes IaaS as "where the consumer is able to deploy and run arbitrary software, which can include operating systems and applications.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] IaaS-cloud providers supply these resources on-demand from their large pools of equipment installed in data centers.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] For wide-area connectivity, customers can use either the Internet or carrier clouds (dedicated virtual private networks).
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] To deploy their applications, cloud users install operating-system images and their application software on the cloud infrastructure.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] In this model, the cloud user patches and maintains the operating systems and the application software.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Cloud providers typically bill IaaS services on a utility computing basis: cost reflects the number of resources allocated and consumed.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] PaaS vendors offer a development environment to application developers.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] The provider typically develops toolkit and standards for development and channels for distribution and payment.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] In the PaaS models, cloud providers deliver a computing platform, typically including an operating system, programming-language execution environment, database, and the web server.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Application developers develop and run their software on a cloud platform instead of directly buying and managing the underlying hardware and software layers.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] With some PaaS, the underlying computer and storage resources scale automatically to match application demand so that the cloud user does not have to allocate resources manually.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Some integration and data management providers also use specialized applications of PaaS as delivery models for data.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Examples include **iPaaS (Integration Platform as a Service)** and **dPaaS (Data Platform as a Service)**. iPaaS enables customers to develop, execute and govern integration flows.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Under the iPaaS integration model, customers drive the development and deployment of integrations without installing or managing any hardware or middleware. dPaaS delivers integration—and data-management—products as a fully managed service.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Under the dPaaS model, the PaaS provider, not the customer, manages the development and execution of programs by building data applications for the customer. dPaaS users access data through data-visualization tools.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] In the software as a service (SaaS) model, users gain access to application software and databases.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Cloud providers manage the infrastructure and platforms that run the applications.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] SaaS is sometimes referred to as "on-demand software" and is usually priced on a pay-per-use basis or using a subscription fee.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] In the SaaS model, cloud providers install and operate application software in the cloud and cloud users access the software from cloud clients.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Cloud users do not manage the cloud infrastructure and platform where the application runs.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] This eliminates the need to install and run the application on the cloud user's own computers, which simplifies maintenance and support.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Cloud applications differ from other applications in their scalability—which can be achieved by cloning tasks onto multiple virtual machines at run-time to meet changing work demand.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Load balancers distribute the work over the set of virtual machines.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] This process is transparent to the cloud user, who sees only a single access-point.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] To accommodate a large number of cloud users, cloud applications can be *multitenant*, meaning that any machine may serve more than one cloud-user organization.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] The pricing model for SaaS applications is typically a monthly or yearly flat fee per user, so prices become scalable and adjustable if users are added or removed at any point.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Proponents claim that SaaS gives a business the potential to reduce IT operational costs by outsourcing hardware and software maintenance and support to the cloud provider.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] This enables the business to reallocate IT operations costs away from hardware/software spending and from personnel expenses, towards meeting other goals.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] In addition, with applications hosted centrally, updates can be released without the need for users to install new software.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] One drawback of SaaS comes with storing the users' data on the cloud provider's server.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] As a result, there could be unauthorized access to the data.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Examples of applications offered as SaaS are games and productivity software like Google Docs and Office Online.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] SaaS applications may be integrated with cloud storage or File hosting services, which is the case with Google Docs being integrated with Google Drive, and Office Online being integrated with OneDrive.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Serverless computing allows customers to use various cloud capabilities without the need to provision, deploy, or manage hardware or software resources, apart from providing their application code or data.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] ISO/IEC 22123-2:2023 classifies serverless alongside Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), and Software as a Service (SaaS) under the broader category of cloud service categories.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Notably, while ISO refers to these classifications as cloud service categories, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) refers to them as service models.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] "A cloud deployment model represents the way in which cloud computing can be organized based on the control and sharing of physical or virtual resources." Cloud deployment models define the fundamental patterns of interaction between cloud customers and cloud providers.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] They do not detail implementation specifics or the configuration of resources.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Private cloud is cloud infrastructure operated solely for a single organization, whether managed internally or by a third party, and hosted either internally or externally.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Undertaking a private cloud project requires significant engagement to virtualize the business environment, and requires the organization to reevaluate decisions about existing resources.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] It can improve business, but every step in the project raises security issues that must be addressed to prevent serious vulnerabilities.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Self-run data centers are generally capital intensive.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] They have a significant physical footprint, requiring allocations of space, hardware, and environmental controls.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] These assets have to be refreshed periodically, resulting in additional capital expenditures.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] They have attracted criticism because users "still have to buy, build, and manage them" and thus do not benefit from less hands-on management, essentially "[lacking] the economic model that makes cloud computing such an intriguing concept".
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Cloud services are considered "public" when they are delivered over the public Internet, and they may be offered as a paid subscription, or free of charge.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Architecturally, there are few differences between public- and private-cloud services, but security concerns increase substantially when services (applications, storage, and other resources) are shared by multiple customers.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Most public-cloud providers offer direct-connection services that allow customers to securely link their legacy data centers to their cloud-resident applications.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Several factors like the functionality of the solutions, cost, integrational and organizational aspects as well as safety & security are influencing the decision of enterprises and organizations to choose a public cloud or on-premises solution.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Varied use cases for hybrid cloud composition exist.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] For example, an organization may store sensitive client data in house on a private cloud application, but interconnect that application to a business intelligence application provided on a public cloud as a software service.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] This example of hybrid cloud extends the capabilities of the enterprise to deliver a specific business service through the addition of externally available public cloud services.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Hybrid cloud adoption depends on a number of factors such as data security and compliance requirements, level of control needed over data, and the applications an organization uses.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Another example of hybrid cloud is one where IT organizations use public cloud computing resources to meet temporary capacity needs that can not be met by the private cloud.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] This capability enables hybrid clouds to employ cloud bursting for scaling across clouds.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Cloud bursting is an application deployment model in which an application runs in a private cloud or data center and "bursts" to a public cloud when the demand for computing capacity increases.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] A primary advantage of cloud bursting and a hybrid cloud model is that an organization pays for extra compute resources only when they are needed.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Cloud bursting enables data centers to create an in-house IT infrastructure that supports average workloads, and use cloud resources from public or private clouds, during spikes in processing demands.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] As a result, only a portion of the potential cost savings of cloud computing is achieved.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] According to ISO/IEC 22123-1: "multi-cloud is a cloud deployment model in which a customer uses public cloud services provided by two or more cloud service providers".
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Poly cloud refers to the use of multiple public clouds for the purpose of leveraging specific services that each provider offers.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] It differs from Multi cloud in that it is not designed to increase flexibility or mitigate against failures but is rather used to allow an organization to achieve more than could be done with a single provider.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] According to International Data Corporation (IDC), global spending on cloud computing services has reached $706 billion and is expected to reach $1.3 trillion by 2025.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Gartner estimated that global public cloud services end-user spending would reach $600 billion by 2023.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] According to a McKinsey & Company report, cloud cost-optimization levers and value-oriented business use cases foresee more than $1 trillion in run-rate EBITDA across Fortune 500 companies as up for grabs in 2030.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] In 2022, more than $1.3 trillion in enterprise IT spending was at stake from the shift to the cloud, growing to almost $1.8 trillion in 2025, according to Gartner.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] The *Communication* set out a series of "digital agenda actions" which the Commission proposed to undertake in order to support the development of a fair and effective market for cloud computing services.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] As of 2025, the three largest cloud computing providers by market share, commonly referred to as hyperscalers, are Amazon Web Services (AWS), Microsoft Azure, and Google Cloud.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] These companies dominate the global cloud market due to their extensive infrastructure, broad service offerings, and scalability.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] In recent years, organizations have increasingly adopted alternative cloud providers, which offer specialized services that distinguish them from hyperscalers.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Alternative cloud providers are often part of multi-cloud strategies, where organizations use multiple cloud services—both from hyperscalers and specialized providers—to optimize performance, compliance, and cost efficiency.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] However, they do not necessarily serve as direct replacements for hyperscalers, as their offerings are typically more specialized.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] The goal of cloud computing is to allow users to take benefit from all of these technologies, without the need for deep knowledge about or expertise with each one of them.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] The cloud aims to cut costs and helps the users focus on their core business instead of being impeded by IT obstacles.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] The main enabling technology for cloud computing is virtualization.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Virtualization software separates a physical computing device into one or more "virtual" devices, each of which can be easily used and managed to perform computing tasks.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] With operating system-level virtualization essentially creating a scalable system of multiple independent computing devices, idle computing resources can be allocated and used more efficiently.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Virtualization provides the agility required to speed up IT operations and reduces cost by increasing infrastructure utilization.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Autonomic computing automates the process through which the user can provision resources on-demand.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] By minimizing user involvement, automation speeds up the process, reduces labor costs and reduces the possibility of human errors.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Cloud computing uses concepts from utility computing to provide metrics for the services used.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cloud-computing] Cloud computing attempts to address QoS (quality of service) and reliability problems of other grid computing models.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Often considered a subset or quantitative tool of managerial accounting, its end goal is to advise the management on how to optimize business practices and processes based on cost efficiency and capability.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Cost accounting provides the detailed cost information that management needs to control current operations and plan for the future.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Cost accounting information is also commonly used in financial accounting, but its primary function is for use by managers to facilitate their decision-making.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] All types of businesses, whether manufacturing, trading or producing services, require cost accounting to track their activities.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Cost accounting has long been used to help managers understand the costs of running a business.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Modern cost accounting originated during the Industrial Revolution when the complexities of running large scale businesses led to the development of systems for recording and tracking costs to help business owners and managers make decisions.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Various techniques used by cost accountants include standard costing and variance analysis, marginal costing and cost volume profit analysis, budgetary control, uniform costing, inter firm comparison, etc.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Evaluation of cost accounting is mainly due to the limitations of financial accounting.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Moreover, maintenance of cost records has been made compulsory in selected industries as notified by the government from time to time.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] In the early industrial age most of the costs incurred by a business were what modern accountants call "variable costs" because they varied directly with the amount of production.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Money was spent on labour, raw materials, the power to run a factory, etc., in direct proportion to production.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Managers could simply total the variable costs for a product and use this as a rough guide for decision-making processes.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Some costs tend to remain the same even during idle periods, unlike variable costs, which rise and fall with volume of work (and thus variable costs are higher in busy periods, and fall during idle periods).
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Over time, these "fixed costs" have become more important to managers.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Examples of fixed costs include the depreciation of plant and equipment, and the cost of departments such as maintenance, tooling, production control, purchasing, quality control, storage and handling, plant supervision and engineering.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] In the early nineteenth century, these costs were of little importance to most businesses.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] However, with the growth of railroads, steel and large scale manufacturing, by the late nineteenth century these costs were often more important than the variable cost of a product, and allocating them to a broad range of products led to bad decision making.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Managers must understand fixed costs in order to make decisions about products and pricing.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] For example: a company produces railway coaches and has only one product.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] To make each coach, the company needs to purchase $60 of raw materials and components and pay 6 labourers $40 each.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Therefore, the total variable cost for each coach was $300.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Knowing that making a coach requires spending $300, managers know they cannot sell below that price without losing money on each coach.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Any price above $300 would make a contribution to the fixed costs of the company.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] If the fixed costs are, say, $1000 per month for rent, insurance and owner's salary, the company could therefore sell 5 coaches per month for a total of $3000 (priced at $600 each), or 10 coaches for a total of $4500 (priced at $450 each), and make a profit of $500 in each case.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] The materials directly contributed to a product and those easily identifiable in the finished product are called **direct materials**.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] For example, paper in books, wood in furniture, plastic in a water tank, and leather in shoes are direct materials.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Other, usually lower cost items or supporting material used in the production of in a finished product are called **indirect materials**.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] For example, lubricants used to keep machines running, or the chemicals used during the garment manufacturing processes.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Furthermore, these can be categorized into three different types of inventories that must be accounted for in different ways; raw materials, work-in-progress, and finished goods.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Any wages paid to workers or a group of workers which may directly co-relate to any specific activity of production, maintenance, transportation of material, or product, and directly associate in the conversion of raw material into finished goods are called **direct labour**.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Wages paid to trainees or apprentices does not come under the category of direct labour as they have no significant value.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] These categories are flexible, sometimes overlapping as different cost accounting principles are applied.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] By function: production, administration, selling and distribution, or research and development.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] By behavior: fixed, variable, or semi-variable.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Fixed costs remain unchanged irrespective of changes in the production volume over a given period of time.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Variable costs change according to the volume of production.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Semi-variable costs are partly fixed and partly variable.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] By controllability: Controllable costs are those which can be controlled or influenced by conscious management action.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Uncontrollable costs cannot be controlled or influenced by conscious management action.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] By normality: normal costs and abnormal costs.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Normal costs arise during routine day-to-day business operations.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Abnormal costs arise because of any abnormal activity or event not part of routine business operations, such as accidents or natural disasters.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] By time: Historical costs and predetermined costs.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Historical costs are costs incurred in the past.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Predetermined costs are computed in advance on basis of factors affecting cost elements.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Differential costs: This cost is the difference in total cost resulting from selecting one alternative over another.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Opportunity costs: The value of a benefit sacrificed in favour of an alternative course of action.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Relevant cost: The relevant cost is a cost which is relevant in various decisions of management.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Replacement cost: This cost is the cost at which existing items of material or fixed assets can be replaced at present or at a future date.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Shutdown cost: Costs incurred if operations are shut down, and which would not occur if operations are continued.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Capacity cost: The cost incurred by a company for providing production, administration and selling and distribution capabilities in order to perform various functions.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Sunk cost: A cost already incurred, which cannot be recovered.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Standard Costing is a technique of Cost Accounting to compare the actual costs with standard costs (that are pre-defined) with the help of Variance Analysis.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] It is used to understand the variations of product costs in manufacturing.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Standard costing allocates fixed costs incurred in an accounting period to the goods produced during that period.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] It also essentially enabled managers to ignore the fixed costs, and look at the results of each period in relation to the "standard cost" for any given product.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] For Example: if the railway coach company normally produced 40 coaches per month, and the fixed costs were still $1000/month, then each coach could be said to incur an Operating Cost/overhead of $25 =($1000 / 40).
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Adding this to the variable costs of $300 per coach produced a full cost of $325 per coach.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] This method tended to slightly distort the resulting unit cost, but in mass-production industries that made one product line, and where the fixed costs were relatively low, the distortion was very minor.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] For Example: if the railway coach company made 100 coaches one month, then the unit cost would become $310 per coach ($300 + ($1000 / 100)).
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] If the next month the company made 50 coaches, then the unit cost = $320 per coach ($300 + ($1000 / 50)), a relatively minor difference.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] As business became more complex and began producing a greater variety of products, the use of cost accounting to make decisions to maximize profitability came into question.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Management circles became increasingly aware of the theory of constraints in the 1980s and began to understand that "every production process has a limiting factor" somewhere in the chain of production.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] As business management learned to identify the constraints, they increasingly adopted throughput accounting to manage them and "maximize the *throughput dollars*" (or other currency) from each unit of constrained resource.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Throughput accounting aims to make the best use of scarce resources (bottleneck) in a JIT (Just in time) environment.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] "Throughput", in this context, refers to the amount of money obtained from sales minus the cost of materials that have gone into making them.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Activity-based costing (ABC) is a system for assigning costs to products based on the activities they require.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] In this case, activities are those regular actions performed inside a company.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] "Talking with the customer regarding invoice questions" is an example of activity inside most companies.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Companies may be moved to adopt ABC by a need to improve costing accuracy, that is, understand better the true costs and profitability of individual products, services, or initiatives.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] ABC gets closer to true costs in these areas by turning many costs that standard cost accounting views as indirect costs essentially into direct costs.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] By contrast, standard cost accounting typically determines so-called indirect and overhead costs simply as a percentage of certain direct costs, which may or may not reflect actual resource usage for individual items.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Under ABC, accountants assign 100% of each employee's time to the different activities performed inside a company (many will use surveys to have the workers themselves assign their time to the different activities).
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] The accountant then can determine the total cost spent on each activity by summing up the percentage of each worker's salary spent on that activity.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] A company can use the resulting activity cost data to determine where to focus its operational improvements.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] For example, a job-based manufacturer may find that a high percentage of its workers are spending their time trying to figure out a hastily written customer order.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Via (ABC) Activity-based costing, the accountants now have a currency amount pegged to the activity of "Researching Customer Work Order Specifications".
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Senior management can now decide how much focus or money to budget for resolving this process deficiency.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Activity-based management includes (but is not restricted to) the use of activity-based costing to manage a business.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] While (ABC) Activity-based costing may be able to pinpoint the cost of each activity and resources into the ultimate product, the process could be tedious, costly and subject to errors.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] As it is a tool for a more accurate way of allocating fixed costs into a product, these fixed costs do not vary according to each month's production volume.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] For example, the elimination of one product would not eliminate the overhead or even direct labour cost assigned to it.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Activity-based costing (ABC) better identifies product costing in the long run, but may not be too helpful in day-to-day decision-making.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Recently, Mocciaro Li Destri, Picone and Minà (2012) proposed a performance and cost measurement system that integrates the Economic Value Added criteria with Process-Based Costing (PBC).
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] The EVA-PBC methodology allows us to implement the EVA management logic not only at the firm level, but also at lower levels of the organization.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] EVA-PBC methodology plays an interesting role in bringing strategy back into financial performance measures.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Lean accounting has developed in recent years to provide the accounting, control, and measurement methods supporting lean manufacturing and other applications of lean thinking such as healthcare, construction, insurance, banking, education, government and other industries.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] There are two main thrusts for Lean Accounting.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] The first is the application of lean methods to the company's accounting, control, and measurement processes.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] This is not different from applying lean methods to any other processes.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] The objective is to eliminate waste, free up capacity, speed up the process, eliminate errors & defects, and make the process clear and understandable.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Lean Accounting does not require the traditional management accounting methods like standard costing, activity-based costing, variance reporting, cost-plus pricing, complex transactional control systems, and untimely and confusing financial reports.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] The cost-volume-profit analysis is the systematic examination of the relationship between selling prices, sales, production volumes, costs, expenses and profits.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] This analysis provides very useful information for decision-making in the management of a company.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] For example, the analysis can be used in establishing sales prices, in the product mix selection to sell, in the decision to choose marketing strategies, and in the analysis of the impact on profits by changes in costs.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] In the current environment of business, a business administration must act and take decisions in a fast and accurate manner.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] As a result, the importance of cost-volume-profit is still increasing as time passes.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] A relationship between the cost, volume and profit is the contribution margin.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] The contribution margin is the revenue excess from sales over variable costs.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] The concept of contribution margin is particularly useful in the planning of business because it gives an insight into the potential profits that a business can generate.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] The contribution margin can also be expressed as a percentage.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] The contribution margin ratio, which is sometimes called the profit-volume ratio, indicates the percentage of each sales dollar available to cover fixed costs and to provide operating revenue.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] The contribution margin ratio measures the effect on operating income of an increase or a decrease in sales volume.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] For example, assume that the management of Fusion, Inc. is studying the effect of adding $80,000 in sales orders.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Multiplying the contribution margin ratio (40%) by the change in sales volume ($80,000) indicates that operating income will increase $32,000 if additional orders are obtained.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Variable costs as a percentage of sales are equal to 100% minus the contribution margin ratio.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] The total contribution margin $432,000, can also be computed directly by multiplying the sales by the contribution margin ratio ($1,080,000 X 40%).
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Relevant cost data or pricing data may be required from the supplier, in order to undertake a "cost realism analysis", also known as a "price realism analysis".
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/cost-accounting] Similarly, where a government agency requests a fixed price submission, provision may be made for a cost or price realism analysis to take place during the evaluation process.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/total-cost-of-ownership] For manufacturing, as TCO is typically compared with doing business overseas, it goes beyond the initial manufacturing cycle time and cost to make parts.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/total-cost-of-ownership] TCO includes a variety of cost of doing business items, for example, ship and re-ship, and opportunity costs, while it also considers incentives developed for an alternative approach.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/total-cost-of-ownership] Incentives and other variables include tax credits, common language, expedited delivery, and customer-oriented supplier visits.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/total-cost-of-ownership] TCO, when incorporated into a financial benefit analysis, provides a cost basis for determining the total economic value of an investment.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/total-cost-of-ownership] Examples include: return on investment, internal rate of return, economic value added, return on information technology, and rapid economic justification.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/total-cost-of-ownership] The roots of this concept date at least back to the first quarter of the twentieth century.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/total-cost-of-ownership] Many different methodologies and software tools have been developed to analyze TCO in various operational contexts.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/total-cost-of-ownership] A TCO analysis includes total cost of acquisition and operating costs, as well as costs related to replacement or upgrades at the end of the life cycle.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/total-cost-of-ownership] A TCO analysis is used to gauge the viability of any capital investment.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/total-cost-of-ownership] An enterprise may use it as a product/process comparison tool.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/total-cost-of-ownership] It is also used by credit markets and financing agencies.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/total-cost-of-ownership] TCO directly relates to an enterprise's asset and/or related systems total costs across all projects and processes, thus giving a picture of the profitability over time.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/total-cost-of-ownership] TCO analysis was popularized by the Gartner Group in 1987.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/total-cost-of-ownership] TCO is applied to the analysis of information technology products, seeking to quantify the financial impact of deploying a product over its life cycle.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/total-cost-of-ownership] These technologies include software and hardware, and training.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/total-cost-of-ownership] In the case of comparing TCO of existing versus proposed solutions, consideration should be put toward costs required to maintain the existing solution that may not necessarily be required for a proposed solution.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/total-cost-of-ownership] Examples include cost of manual processing that are only required to support lack of existing automation, and extended support personnel.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/total-cost-of-ownership] Total cost of ownership can be applied to the structure and systems of a single building or a campus of buildings.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/total-cost-of-ownership] Pioneered by Doug Christensen and the facilities department at Brigham Young University starting in the 1980s, the concept gained more traction in educational facilities in the early 21st century.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/total-cost-of-ownership] A key objective of planning, constructing, operating, and managing buildings via TCO principals is for building owners and facility professionals to predict needs and deliver data-driven results.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/total-cost-of-ownership] TCO can be applied any time during the life of a facility asset to manage cost inputs for the life of the structure or system into the future.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/total-cost-of-ownership] APPA, an ANSI Accredited Standards Developer, published *APPA 1000-1 – Total Cost of Ownership for Facilities Asset Management (TCO) – Part 1: Key Principles* as an American National Standard in December 2017.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/total-cost-of-ownership] APPA 1000-1 provides financial officers, facility professionals, architects, planners, construction workforce, and operations and maintenance (O&M) personnel the foundation of a standardized and holistic approach to implementing TCO key principles.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/total-cost-of-ownership] Implementation of TCO key principles can improve decision making, maximizing financial strategies over the life of an asset, starting at the planning and design stage and extends to the end of the asset's life.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/total-cost-of-ownership] APPA 1000-2, slated for publication in 2019, will focus on implementation and application of key TCO principals in facility management.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/total-cost-of-ownership] The TCO concept is easily applicable to the transportation industry and to motor vehicle ownership, for example, the TCO defines the cost of owning an automobile from the time of purchase by the owner, through its operation and maintenance to the time it leaves the possession of the owner.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/total-cost-of-ownership] Comparative TCO studies between various models help consumers choose a car to fit their needs and budget.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/total-cost-of-ownership] For personal vehicles in the United States, AAA's annual *Your Driving Costs* study estimated the average total cost of new-vehicle ownership at $11,577 per year in 2025, driven by depreciation, financing, fuel, insurance, maintenance, and license fees.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/total-cost-of-ownership] In the truck industry, TCO is an essential factor for truck fleet managers.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/total-cost-of-ownership] By calculating the Total Cost of Ownership of a truck, the truck manager obtains a price per kilometer that varies according to fuel costs, the purchase price, and the resale price of the truck.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/total-cost-of-ownership] If the truck is financed, the TCO also varies according to the interest rate on the loan.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/total-cost-of-ownership] These factors in the trucking industry allow managers to make a clearer choice about which truck to select for their truck fleet, because when a transportation company wants to acquire 1 to 10 trucks, TCO is an essential factor to consider for the company's cash flow.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/total-cost-of-ownership] TCO does not assess how well a solution offers value for money, or how well it fits with an organisation's strategic objectives.
[src:cloud-cost-optimization/total-cost-of-ownership] Some TCO analyses may include social and environmental costs but this is not always the case.
